Creative Commons BY-NC-SA 4.0
The Creative Commons BY-NC-SA 4.0 (Attribution–NonCommercial–ShareAlike 4.0 International) license is a widely used open content license allowing others to remix, adapt, and build upon a work noncommercially, as long as they credit the author and license new creations under identical terms. It balances openness with restrictions on commercial use.

Key facts
Full name: Creative Commons Attribution–NonCommercial–ShareAlike 4.0 International

Abbreviation: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

Release year: 2013

License type: Open content, noncommercial

Key permissions: Share and adapt with attribution and share-alike conditions

Core terms
Under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, users may copy, redistribute, remix, and transform the licensed material in any medium or format for noncommercial purposes. Attribution must be given to the creator, and any derivative works must be distributed under the same license. The license also prohibits applying additional legal restrictions, such as DRM, that would limit others’ rights under the license.

Attribution and share-alike requirements
Attribution requires identifying the creator, providing a link to the license, and indicating if changes were made. “ShareAlike” means adaptations must carry the same CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license, ensuring the same freedoms and restrictions pass on to subsequent users. This provision maintains an open, collaborative ecosystem of content reuse.

Noncommercial limitation
The “NonCommercial” clause forbids using the licensed material for primarily commercial advantage or monetary compensation. However, Creative Commons leaves interpretation flexible to accommodate diverse global contexts, which can lead to differing understandings of what counts as commercial activity.

Use and adoption
CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 is popular among educators, artists, and open culture projects that want to encourage reuse without enabling commercial exploitation. It is one of six main Creative Commons licenses and is interoperable across jurisdictions, thanks to its international wording and simplified legal code.

